{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472595","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472595"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:00:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:00:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1547"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1547","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1547"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.12,0.02,0.75,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1547"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90835"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1547","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1547"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1547"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74898"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"819"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2367"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31134"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42338"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44052"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90835","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90835"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 15-year-old girl presents with her mother to the General Practice clinic with an itchy lesion on her upper arm that has been growing in size over the last month. She is very self-conscious about it and is worried it will continue to grow in size and appear on other areas of her body. She has been applying topical steroid ointment to the affected area.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination there is a single annular lesion measuring 3 x 3 cm on the lateral side of her upper arm. It has a peripheral scaly red rim with an area of clearing in the centre (Image). There are no similar lesions elsewhere.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Erythema multiforme","Psoriasis","Scabies","Tinea corporis","Pityriasis rosea"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is \u003Cstrong\u003Etinea corporis\u003C/strong\u003E, a fungal infection also known as \u201cringworm\u201d or dermatophyte infection. Dermatophytes include three genera: \u003Cem\u003ETrichophyton\u003C/em\u003E, \u003Cem\u003EMicrosporum\u003C/em\u003E, and \u003Cem\u003EEpidermophyton\u003C/em\u003E. Tinea infections are classified by the affected site, e.g. corporis (body), cruris (groin), pedis (feet). There is a central pale area surrounded by an erythematous, scaly ring. Skin scrapings should be taken and it should be treated with topical antifungals for at least 1 week (eg. terbinafine cream). If there are multiple lesions or no improvement, oral antifungals can be considered.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETinea infections are contagious. Risk factors include living in hot humid climates, diabetes, immunodeficiency, hyperhidrosis, xerosis, ichthyosis, household crowding, infection of close contacts, wearing occlusive clothing, and recreational activities involving close contact with others including shared change rooms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EErythema multiforme\u003C/strong\u003E is a hypersensitivity reaction most commonly associated with infection and characterised by target lesions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPsoriasis\u003C/strong\u003E is an inflammatory condition characterised by clearly defined erythematous plaques with silvery scale.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScabies\u003C/strong\u003E is a contagious infestation with the mite \u003Cem\u003ESarcoptes scabiei. \u003C/em\u003ECommon skin findings of scabies include intense pruritis with secondary excoriation, generalised hypersensitivity erythematous rash, and burrows commonly in the web spaces of the fingers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPityriasis rosea \u003C/strong\u003Eis a rash that occurs after a viral infection. Typically, a herald patch of a single erythematous plaque with trailing scale appears before the secondary rash of similar smaller patches occurs.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Tinea is a dermatophyte infection classified by affected body site."],"references":["Ely JW, Rosenfeld S, Seabury Stone M. Diagnosis and management of tinea infections. Am Fam Physician. 2014;90(10):702-10. Available at: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2014/1115/p702.html","Leung AK, Lam JM, Leong KF, Hon KL. Tinea corporis: an updated review. Drugs Context. 2020;9:2020-5-6. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7375854/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74898"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1547"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17439"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17439","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17439"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9d21b188-09cb-495b-ab89-fb691e6e3b3e.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9d21b188-09cb-495b-ab89-fb691e6e3b3e.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":448,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74898","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74898"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-14T16:55:13+10:30","up